<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-352-762  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 352 762.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  June 8 1989 n1167 p24(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>More space less floor. (storing documents with image processing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Townsend, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Storing documents on disk or tape or optical media is becomingeasier with new hardware and software capable of sophisticatedimage processing.andP;  The components of an image processing systemare a scanner for image input, a processor, high capacity storage,a high-resolution screen and a high-resolution printer.andP;  Forsimply archiving documents for legal reasons, a stand-alone imageprocessor can provide economical storage because efficientretrieval is not a primary concern in such a system.andP;  A networkedimage processing system makes documents available to multipleusers.andP;  A wide variety of systems is available from specialtysuppliers and large vendors including IBM.andP;  Such systems makemanagement and retrieval more efficient, often costing less thanmaintaining files of hard copies in high-rent business districts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image ProcessingDocument Management SystemsStorage CapacityFile Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>